It makes me think of Galicia, Spain and my year as an Erasmus student. It's part of a "best of" compilation of this band. They're a famous Gallego folk band, one of the best known. They headlined a celtic music festival I went to in Galicia last summer, so I downloaded this album to remind myself of what they sounded like. It's not really so much my thing - undoubtedly they're a very accomplished band but this track has a very fado influenced style, which I liked at one time but not so much now. I prefer their more celtic sounding stuff. 

 No, I don't knwo this one particularly. But hearing the music and the Gallego language does make me think of last summer, and of my experiences living there over ten years ago.
coded_text_excerpt: I prefer their more celtic sounding stuff.

full_response_text: Haha, that this is a track from one of the most expensive records I ever bought... I have this song on a 5x record box set which cost $130 a few years ago. I love this band, they only ever released weird bootleg live albums, without ever making a 'proper' album. This is my favourite song of theirs, and I have at least ten versions of it- they're all full of distortion and noise, often with bad sound quality and people talking, feedback, shambolic performances etc but it all adds to the strange chaotic wildness of the band. Even though it's slow track, the lo-fi way that it's recorded and the sort of unpredictable character of all of this band's recordings mean that its kind of exciting, it feels as if the wheels might fall off and it collapse, or it might manage to wobble along into something amazing. Because I have a bunch of different versions of this track by the same band, it means I'm not completely certain what will happen next. It's interesting, I feel like I have a relationship

full_response_text: I love the energy and rhythmicity of it. As soon as it started, I was bouncing around in my chair! I've seen the band play live, and when they perform this piece the percussionist sits at the front of the stage, and strikes a variety of objects extremely rapidly all the way through the piece, to a very tight and well-defined rhythm. I can visualise the physical effort and control he displays, and that feeds into my experience of the piece. But it's also generally a very lively and joyful piece -- I smile when I hear it -- so I don't feel the percussionist's physical effort as a strain, as such: more like extremely energetic dancing. I bought the CD at a gig by the Graham Fitkin band. I wanted to have the music to listen to, because I enjoy the pieces per se -- but it also lets me carry a bit of the memory of the gig around with me. As I mentioned above: energy, rhythmicity, joyfulness, memories of great nights spent watching the band. I feel I have a very physical relationship with thi
coded_text_excerpt: I'm also a keen follower of Graham Fitkin and his music, so when I hear this track (or indeed any of his) it reminds me of that part of my musical identity: amongst the many things that I am as a musical being, I identify as a "Graham Fitkin fan", and this piece somehow serves to strengthen the relationship I feel with Graham (or at least his public persona) and his music.

I love Bartok, and particularly enjoy the folk influence in his rhythms, melodies and harmonies, but for various reasons this I haven't put this on for a while. I trained as a classical musician during my teenage years, and used to listen to a lot of classical music then -- this piece included. I remember having very strong experiences listening to this piece, particularly the last movement: real rushes of overwhelming joy and excitement. I bought the CD many years ago, and it was one of a group of particularly loved CDs that I uploaded to my iPod when I was first given it. Strong rhythm, folk influences on melody and harmony, contrapuntal interest, subtle and beautiful orchestration. It reminds me very much of the intense musical experiences I used to have listening to classical music as a young person.
